DOCREF="FT933-10881"
SELECTOR="H"
SUMMARIZER="I">  

Foes of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) are mobilizing
with a small budget.  Actions include a Declaration of War against
NAFTA in California, and alternative dinner menus, featuring toxic
Mexican produce, for the Deputy U.S. Trade Representative in
Washington State.  The anti-NAFTA czar, Jim Jontz, has a campaign
office, field legislative directors, and organizations in 41 states.
President Clinton has not yet named his NAFTA czar, but supporters,
mostly within the business community, are spending millions to
convince Congress to pass the agreement.  Both sides are waiting for
side agreements on labor and environment to be finalized this
week.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d44"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT933-5709"
SELECTOR="H"
SUMMARIZER="I">  

William Daley is the administration's point man on the North American
Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) fight.  Daley, brother of the current
mayor of Chicago and son of the legendary mayor, is a smooth behind
the scene operator with ties in organized labor and Washington.  He
ran Clinton's campaign in Illinois.  Polls show 66% of Americans do
not support the agreement, which must be ratified by January 1 or
disappear.  Core democratic constituencies as well as Ross Perot
oppose NAFTA.  Ratification in Congress requires 218 votes.  Now the
administration can count on 125 republicans and 20 democrats.  Daley
will need to muster 73 more.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d44"
TYPE="PERDOC"
