SUMMARIZER="I">  

Both sides of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) issues
are active, as a new Wall Street Journal poll shows 36% of Americans
opposing the agreement with only 25% supporting it.  Fifty percent do
not believe more jobs will be gained than lost, and 54% think wages
will go down.  Pro-NAFTA activities included testimony from four ex-
presidents, administration officials on speaking tours, and government
agencies passing out propaganda.  Gore has praised NAFTA's
environmental safeguards.  Except for the speaker, House democratic
leaders are silent.  Anti-NAFTA activity involves grassroots' exploits
and strategic planning with warnings that 20 years of environmental
protection work will be undermined.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d44"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT934-13350"
SELECTOR="H"
SUMMARIZER="I">  

The Clinton administration soon will announce support for the North
American Development Bank, which is expected to gain the votes of at
least eight Hispanic representatives for the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA).  The administration now believes it has 200-210 of
the 218 votes needed for ratification.  Clinton is giving impassioned
speeches, inviting undecided representatives to the White House, and
sending cabinet members to congressional districts.  Anti-NAFTA forces
count 5-10 republicans against and 190-200 democrats against, with
10-15 democrats leaning against. Anti-NAFTA activities include labor
union exhibits and speeches by workers who lost their jobs to
Mexico.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d44"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT934-10911"
SELECTOR="H"
SUMMARIZER="I">  

The House of Representatives' vote on the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA) will be on November 16.  A simple majority of 218
votes is needed for passage.  Two factions that do not follow
conventional party lines exist. One anti- NAFTA leader characterized
the battle as the "elite" against the "populists".  The pro- faction
consists of the administration, the republican leadership, most big
business leaders, some democrats, and some prominent environmental
groups. The anti-faction includes labor, some democratic leaders
including most of the black and Hispanic caucuses,
ultra-conservatives, and Nader and Perot.  The stakes are high for
Clinton as his pro-NAFTA campaign goes into full swing.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d44"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT934-9116"
