SUMMARIZER="I">  

The battle of the North American Free Trade Agreement has moved into
the congressional districts for the holiday weekend.  Pro-NAFTA forces
claim victory for Vice-president Gore in his recent debate with Ross
Perot.  Perot is under attack from Mexico for statements he made.  One
poll has popular support rising from 34% to 57%.  Opponents believe
fear of job and investment losses will hold sway and one leader claims
219 votes against the pact. Opposition rallies, marches, and meetings
are planned.  The administration claims 192 votes and is financing a
campaign for voters to send NAFTA support telegrams to their
representatives.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d44"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT934-8748"
SELECTOR="H"
SUMMARIZER="I">  

Investors like the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).  They
believe it will lift profits because of a more open trading
environment and that the U.S. will have the greatest growth in
exports.  They fear if it is defeated an era of protectionism will
begin, the world economic growth will slow, and there will be
inflation.  Political costs of failure will be the Clinton
administration's loss of credibility and effectiveness at home and in
any future trade negotiations.  Although the up-coming vote is too
close to call, some believe Gore's success in the debate with Perot
has swayed public opinion.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d44"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT934-8628"
SELECTOR="H"
SUMMARIZER="I">  

An anti-North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) rally in Richmond,
Virginia, drew a small number on Saturday.  The rally was aimed at the
three Virginian representatives still undecided on the NAFTA vote next
week.  The ralliers "mostly union members and Perot followers" claimed
NAFTA undermines the constitution, putting decisions in the hands of
international panels.  Companies and jobs would move to Mexico.  The
Virginia business community has been lobbying for NAFTA since March.
Anti-NAFTA forces declared they only have votes to give, while Clinton
has been promising projects for the districts of the undecided
representatives.</SUM>

<SUM
